You said:
what does the MIT license do?


ChatGPT said:
The MIT License is one of the most popular and permissive open-source software licenses. Here's a quick breakdown of what it does and doesn't do:

âœ… What the MIT License Allows
It gives users broad freedom to:

ğŸ”“ Use your code for any purpose â€” personal, commercial, or educational.

ğŸ› ï¸ Modify it â€” adapt or change the code however they like.

ğŸ“¤ Distribute it â€” share original or modified versions.

ğŸ’¼ Re-license or sell software built on top of it.

ğŸ“œ What It Requires
ğŸ“ They must include the original license and copyright notice
with any copies or substantial portions of the code.

ğŸš« What It Doesn't Do
âŒ It doesn't restrict what people can do with your code.

âŒ It doesn't protect you from people using your code unethically or commercially without giving back.

âŒ It doesnâ€™t provide a patent license, although this is rarely an issue unless you're doing something highly innovative at a low level.

ğŸ§  Why Itâ€™s a Good Fit for Chiron Guild (Initially)
âš™ï¸ Encourages maximum participation and contribution

ğŸš€ Speeds up adoption by individuals and other projects

ğŸª Aligns with open, transparent, community-led development

ğŸ§© You can re-license parts later (especially proprietary tools or AI models)

If you ever want more restrictions (e.g., requiring contributions to be shared back), you could consider:

GNU GPLv3 (more protective, viral open source)

