You said:
tell me more about GNU GPLv3 


ChatGPT said:
The GNU General Public License version 3 (GPLv3) is a strong copyleft license created by the Free Software Foundation. Itâ€™s designed to ensure that software remains free (as in freedom) for all users â€” not just now, but forever.

Hereâ€™s a breakdown of what makes GPLv3 unique:

âœ… What GPLv3 Allows
ğŸ›  Use, modify, and distribute the code freely.

ğŸ§© Combine with other GPL-compatible code or modules.

ğŸ’¡ Build upon it commercially â€” but with conditions.

ğŸ“œ What GPLv3 Requires
This is where it differs significantly from MIT:

1. Copyleft (or â€œShare Alikeâ€)
If you distribute your modified version of the code (or a program that includes it), you must also distribute your source code under the same GPLv3 license.

This ensures that the software and all its derivatives stay open.

2. Preserve Notices
You must keep the original copyright and license notices.

You must also state any significant changes youâ€™ve made.

3. License Grant to All
Anyone who gets a copy of the code gets the same rights you had, with no additional restrictions.

ğŸ” Additional Protections in v3 (vs v2)
ğŸ›¡ Tivoization ban: Companies canâ€™t lock down hardware to prevent modified GPLv3 software from running on it.

ğŸ“¦ Patent protection: If you distribute GPLv3 software, you canâ€™t sue users over patent claims related to that software.

ğŸŒ Anti-DRM stance: You canâ€™t use GPL software to create Digital Rights Management systems that block user freedom.

âŒ What You Canâ€™t Do Under GPLv3
âŒ You canâ€™t make a derivative and close-source it.

âŒ You canâ€™t distribute binaries or compiled versions without also offering source code.

âŒ You canâ€™t add more restrictive terms (e.g. NDA, private use only).

ğŸ§  When to Use GPLv3 (Pros)
Use it when you want to:

Ensure your code remains free and canâ€™t be privatized.

Protect user freedom in software and hardware environments.

Build a commons â€” a shared pool of code that always gives back.

ğŸ§© When Not to Use GPLv3 (Cons)
Avoid it if you:

Want maximum adoption by industry or startups (many avoid GPL due to obligations).

Plan to allow closed-source or proprietary tools in the ecosystem.

Donâ€™t want to enforce copyleft obligations or deal with license complexity.

ğŸ†š Summary: GPLv3 vs MIT
Feature	MIT	GPLv3
Freedom to Use	âœ… Full	âœ… Full
Freedom to Modify	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes
Freedom to Re-license	âœ… Yes (including proprietary)	âŒ Must stay GPL
Required to Share Modifications	âŒ No	âœ… Yes, if redistributed
Commercial Use	âœ… Easy	âš ï¸ Requires GPL compliance
Patent Protection	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
DRM Restrictions	âŒ None	âœ… Prohibited

If Chiron Guild wants to:

Protect open contributions,

Avoid extractive corporate use without giving back,

And keep core infrastructure cooperativeâ€¦

Then GPLv3 (or a hybrid model) might be a strong fit â€” especially for parts of the system intended to stay fully in the commons.

Would you like to explore combining MIT and GPLv3 approaches (e.g., dual licensing or per-module licenses)?





